  "text": "Edge-based methods as Sobel, Canny detectors, Roberts, Prewitt, LoG are usually not effective for SAR images since they use gradient detectors based on the difference between neighboring pixel values, which fails in the presence of speckle noise. Improvements to edgebased methods in Moigne and Tilton [CITATION_1] integrated edges produced by a Canny detector with region growing aiming to minimize the Hausdorff distance between edge maps and region boundaries. This algorithm performed well in Landsat Thematic Mapper (TM) images, but requires a more suitable edge detector to be useful in SAR images. Also, edge strength estimation in speckled images SAR can be accomplished by using ratio-based edge detectors which evaluate transition between uniform areas. Improved edge detectors customized for SAR image segmentation utilizes a sliding window over the image to calculate the ratio of means given a neighborhood definition. These detectors compare the obtained ratio with a threshold that is calculated based on a probability of false alarm (pf a) to determine whether an edge is present or not [7; 8; 9; 10] , an useful criterium considered in the current paper.",
